Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe. [File, Standard]  The National Government has revised the dusk-to-dawn curfew in 13 Nyanza, Western and Rift Valley counties to 7pm to 4am beginning Friday, June 18.  The Ministry of Health says the move has been arrived at to reduce the Covid-19 positivity rate in the regional areas.  The 13 counties, which will operate under the new curfew hours, are: Busia, Vihiga, Kisii, Nyamira, Kakamega, Bungoma, Kericho, Bomet, Trans Nzoia, Kisumu, Siaya, Homa-Bay and Migori.  The Ministry of Health said the positivity rate in the 13 regions averages 21 per cent, while that of the remaining parts of the country is at 9 per cent.  Regulations for the new Covid-19 hotspot zone   Hail Kemsa for creating an efficient business environment, with instant tenders on offer  Mbagathi: Come for second Covid-19 jab... Sorry, we have none  Men dominate the smartphone market in Kenya, survey The Government also barred worship to contain the spike.  “All forms of physical/congressional worship (churches, mosques, temples and shrines) in the hotspot counties are suspended for a period of 30 days,” said Health CS Mutahi Kagwe in an announcement Thursday.   Will the Government lift the ongoing countrywide curfew when it expires at midnight tonight?  Tracking Covid-19: Kenya records 324 new cases, 10 deaths in last 24 hours  Covid Downward Trend: Kenya records 86 new Covid-19 cases with positivity rate now at 3.1% By John Ngumi | 14 minutes ago By Winfrey Owino | 42 minutes ago By Josphat Thiong'o | 2 hours ago By Judah Ben-Hur | 4 hours ago